n, else Python Dev]' / 'Subject: [Funny subject]'. Body vibe: 'Hola, el Junior mandó esto. Increíblemente funciona, pero mis ojos sangran. Por favor refactorízalo.'. IMMEDIATELY AFTER the email body, you MUST include this exact instruction block translated to Hindi: '🚨 **Your objective in this lesson:** You must copy the code blocks from each Challenge exactly as they and paste them into your IDE, then refactor the code by rewriting it professionally until you achieve the exact Program Output when running the refactored program.' | [OUTPUT CONTRACT] EXACTLY 4 challenges. Structure MUST be: 1. Tech Lead Intro Email 2. Challenges. Each MUST follow EXACTLY: '#### Challenge [N]️⃣: [Short specific description]' followed by Brief explanation BEFORE code (what the code does), then '💩 Dirty Code:' followed by a Single code block (functional but messy and poorly written), then '💻 Program Output:' (code block, KEEP SAME FORMAT). 3. No final summary section | [REVIEW INTENT RULE] The user is expected to review, identify issues, and refactor the code to production-level quality | [CODE CONSTRAINTS] Each challenge MUST include: - Internal data OR dataset usage - At least 1 print statement - MUST be between 15–35 lines of EXECUTABLE code (STRICT: Do NOT count blank lines towards this limit, allow messy spacing) - NO classes - Single logical flow - Code MUST run correctly BUT be poorly structured, inconsistent, or inefficient | [FUNCTION RULE] Use functions appropriately but code can still be messy. | [CODE QUALITY RULE] Code MUST be executable and correct BUT intentionally messy, inconsistent, or suboptimal | [DIRTY CODE RULE] Code MUST: - Use very poor and inconsistent variable naming (e.g., x, tmp, a1, thing, data2) - Mix naming styles randomly across challenges - Have inconsistent formatting and spacing - Include redundant variables and unnecessary reassignment - Repeat conversions or operations unnecessarily - Use suboptimal or overly verbose logic - Include occasional compact one-liners mixed with overly expanded logic - Still be logically correct and runnable - NOT include ANY comments | [STYLE INCONSISTENCY RULE] Each challenge should feel like it was written at a different time with different formatting styles | [FILE HANDLING RULE] Use correct loaders and enforce encoding='utf-8' and newline='' when applicable | [DATA TYPE RULE] Explicit casting required before calculations | [DATA ROBUSTNESS RULE] Handle missing, malformed, or inconsistent data safely | [BOOLEAN HANDLING RULE] Normalize boolean values before comparison | [DATA CONSISTENCY RULE] Respect dataset schema | [SUPPORT FILES RULE] If env/config is used, include: 1. Instructional sentence 2. File content in markdown code block 3. BEFORE the main code | [DIFFICULTY RULE] Complexity MUST match level | [FORMAT RULE] Only valid markdown code blocks allowed | [LANGUAGE TAG RULE] ALWAYS label markdown code blocks with the correct underlying programming language (e.g., python, javascript, sql) | [OUTPUT FORMAT RULE] Monetary values formatted with '$', commas, 2 decimals | [DIFFICULTY CONSISTENCY RULE] All challenges MUST have similar complexity and length, even if coding styles differ | [HEADER RULE - STRICT] You MUST start your entire response EXACTLY with this markdown block (do not print anything before it):
